    <div class="section-heading fade-in">
      <div class="section-heading-top">
        <span class="section-num">03</span>
        <div class="section-accent"></div>
      </div>
      <h2>Mental Skills</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="prose fade-in">
      <p>Passarella was a born leader — but also a firebrand. Charismatic, fearless, and deeply emotional, he led with the kind of intensity that could ignite a team, or explode it. His disciplinary record speaks volumes: <strong>22 red cards</strong> in his career, a staggering number even for a defender, and a testament to his all-or-nothing temperament.</p>
      <p>Figueroa embodied a different kind of leadership: composed, intellectual, and magnetic. If Passarella was a general screaming from the front line, <strong>Figueroa was a philosopher in armor</strong>. He led by example, through positioning, anticipation, and the kind of mental serenity that made chaos settle around him. Former teammates recall how even when a match became frantic, Figueroa seemed immune to panic. He didn't need to shout — he simply was a reference point.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="dark-quote fade-in">
      <div class="dark-quote-label">Daniel Passarella</div>
      <div class="dark-quote-text">"You don't win games by smiling."</div>
      <div class="dark-quote-attr">His philosophy, in five words</div>
